{"author":{"id":"8e1777f58c0cfe5478428be8f9fcbfe90d25e44689578335da8fc2246fe0915a"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1459979481,"nonce":"Tcku0+seR5xv1Hg2CyFcC6+2Hw0=","metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDIwNjU4NjczOQ==","github-url":"https://github.com/galaxyproject/tools-iuc/issues/716#issuecomment-206586739"},"message":"Hi all,\n\nsorry to be so late to this discussion, I'm on a workshop these days. \nA few points:\n- I'm fine with moving the DESeq2 script back into Galaxy's wrapper. It used to be there and we can move it back if @mikelove does not need it in his repo, which seems to be the case.\n- the script is currently available one the BioC github mirror and available from BioC, so it is not hidden at all\n- the final wrapper will have support for metadata column names and will follow the 16.04 tool specifications\n- I disagree that dependencies are getting more complicated. Essentially `depot` is a mirror for tarballs. If we store binaries or wheels there, all the recipes are generated with Starforge and on github, so completely transparent. Conda will hopefully replace tool_dependencies and Starforge soon, so in the end you have only Conda packages. The source from Conda packages are mirrored to depot and we can build automatic Docker containers from Conda. So the flow is like this:\n\ndepot \u003c- tarball -\u003e Conda -\u003e Docker \n\n@lparsons feel free to enhance the help section of DESeq2, I always feel that it's hard to explain this in a correct but easy to understand way.","files":null}]}